	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64118331"><p><div class="quote"><p>Basically there's three camps.</p><p>Proprietary = This is our stuff, and no outside help is wanted</p></div><p>That is not accurate. There are proprietary options that have many of the features of FOSS. You describe a proprietary binary license, but there is sometimes a proprietary source license. Especially for libraries. With a source license you are free to modify and build your own code for your distribution. Just like FOSS. However unlike FOSS, your customer that get's your binary has no right to the source code.<br> <br>

So proprietary can extend source code rights one generation, to direct customers only.<br>
Where FOSS<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64118331">

