	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64119089"><p>Of course forking is an option.  A fork can be *really* lightweight. In your case, you make a fork, make your change and pull request, and if you have headwinds you just periodically rebase your fork, checking if your fix has been included or an equivalent.  You don't have to accept pull requests, you don't have to field issues.  You just have to let git do the rebasing ever so often and track the upstream activity.  The Xorg/Wireshark are examples where the entire community was getting cut off, and someone<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64119089">

